Just change the `switch` to `if`. There is no need for `instanceof`:

	public boolean isOwned(Marker m){
		if(m == Sharpie.BLUE || m == Sharpie.BLACK || m == Crayola.GREEN)
			return true;
		return false;
	}

Looks like a good scenario to try new Java Feature [Sealed Interface][1] and [Pattern Matching for switch Expressions][2](* this is a preview feature as at jdk 17)  

First make `Marker` as sealed interface
```
public sealed interface Marker permits Crayola, Sharpie {}
```
Then we can use switch expression to get rid of those `instanceof` checking.
```
    public boolean isOwned(Marker marker) {
        boolean isOwned = switch (marker) {
            case Sharpie s -&gt; s == Sharpie.BLACK || s == Sharpie.BLUE;
            case Crayola c -&gt; c == Crayola.GREEN;
        };
        return isOwned;
    }
```


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/language/sealed-classes-and-interfaces.html
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/language/pattern-matching-switch-expressions-and-statements.html

